04744nam a22006855i 9780748629022DE-B159720220329044247.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220329t20222013stk    fo  d z      eng d  a2013412916  a97807486290227 a10.1515/97807486290222doi  a(DE-B1597)616198  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  astkcGB-SCT00aDG252.6b.S74 2013 4aDG231b.S74 2013 7aHIS0020202bisacsh04a937.022231 aSteel, Catherine, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe End of the Roman Republic 146 to 44 BC :bConquest and Crisis /cCatherine Steel. 1aEdinburgh : bEdinburgh University Press, c[2022] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (320 p.) :b1 Maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Edinburgh History of Ancient Rome : EHAR00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tSeries editor’s preface -- tAuthor’s preface -- tAbbreviations -- tMaps -- tIntroduction -- t1. The crises of the later second century bc -- t2. Domestic politics: violence and its accommodation -- t3. Imperial power: failure and control -- t4. The Social War, civil war and the imposition of a new order -- t5. The limits of autocracy -- t6. The end of the Republic, 70–44 bc -- t7. Imperial expansion: novelty and success -- t8. Elite competition, popular discontent and the failure of collective government -- tChronology -- tGuide to further reading -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 146 BC the armies of Rome destroyed Carthage and emerged as the decisive victors of the Third Punic War. The Carthaginian population was sold and its territory became the Roman province of Africa. In the same year and on the other side of the Mediterranean Roman troops sacked Corinth, the final blow in the defeat of the Achaean conspiracy: thereafter Greece was effectively administered by Rome. Rome was now supreme in Italy, the Balkans, Greece, Macedonia, Sicily, and North Africa, and its power and influence were advancing in all directions. However, not all was well. The unchecked seizure of huge tracts of land in Italy and its farming by vast numbers of newly imported slaves allowed an elite of usually absentee landlords to amass enormous and conspicuous fortunes. Insecurity and resentment fed the gulf between rich and poor in Rome and erupted in a series of violent upheavals in the politics and institutions of the Republic. These were exacerbated by slave revolts and invasions from the east. The instigation of Rome's first professional army to resolve the crises soon made its generals - Sulla, then Pompey, then Caesar - all too powerful. Meanwhile Greek ideas and culture had invaded Rome, contributing to the subversion of the Roman ideal of the free citizen, farmer of his own land, duty-bound to fight in its defence. Catherine Steel tells history of this crucial and turbulent century, focussing on the issues of freedom, honour, power, greed and ambition, and the cherished but abused institutions of the Republic which were central to events then and which have preoccupied historians ever since.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 0aPunic War, 3rd, 149-146 B.C. 4aClassics & Ancient History. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / Rome.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311078046840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978074862902240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780748629022423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780748629022/original  a978-3-11-078046-8  Edinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV